I am creating a microservice-based system in NestJS and need assistance with the service architecture and database design. Please provide the following:

  1. A breakdown of the microservices and their respective functions.
  2. A well-organized database design, including relationships between entities.

Key System Requirements:

  • There are five user types: Superadmin, Farmer, Cooperative, Enumerator, and Vendor.
  • All users have profiles with common fields: First name, Last name, Email, Phone number, Password.
  • User verification can be done via phone or email, but only one (the verified method) will be used for notifications.

User-Specific Requirements:

  • Farmers:

    • Can either be part of a cooperative or operate independently.
    • Farmersâ profiles must be verified using their National Identification Number (NIN).
    • Can manage their farms (CRUD) with attributes such as farm name, location, land area, active season, and products. Duplicate farms in the same location are not allowed.

  • Cooperatives:

    • Can view and verify their farmers' profiles.
    • Can add new farmers.

  • Vendors:

    • Register by providing organization details (name, registration date, CAC number).
    • Make payments via a specified payment gateway (managed in settings by the admin).
    • Can manage their products and services (CRUD).

  • Enumerators:

    • Physically verify farms registered by farmers by cross-checking the data provided.

  • Admin:

    • Manages the entire system, including adding opportunities for all users.
    • Administers a cropping calendar that shows seasonal crop details and their requirements (e.g., no vegetation, dense vegetation, harvesting stages, etc.).
    • Administers market information showing product prices, locations, and other details such as coordinates, market date, size, LGA, and ward. This data may also come from external sources.

Other Functionalities:

  • Blogging/CMS: The platform includes a blogging system for content management.
  • Opportunities: Admin adds opportunities that are viewable by all users.

Payment:

  • Payment Gateway: Vendors make payments through a specific payment gateway configured by the admin.

Please consider the following:

  • The database should be designed to handle the relationships between the different user types and their specific actions.
  • Use a clean and modular approach for the microservices, ensuring scalability and separation of concerns.
